l your use cases Scalable: Can grow with your business No-Code Friendly: Minimal technical knowledge required Workflow Automation Sequence: Copy 📊 Spreadsheet Data → 🎨 Canva Design Generation → 📦 Shopify Upload → 🖨️ POD Platform Sync → 📈 Performance monitoring (Manual)              (Zerowork)              (Pabbly Connect)     (Make.com)         (Pabbly Connect) 🧠 AI Agent Recommendation System To create the AI agent that selects the best tool for each scenario, you can build it using AgenticFlow with this decision matrix: Decision Tree Logic: Task Type Analysis: Web automation, API integration, data processing, or hybrid Complexity Assessment: Simple trigger-action vs multi-step workflows Integration Requirements: Which platforms need to connect Volume Considerations: Bulk operations vs individual tasks Budget Constraints: Lifetime deals vs monthly subscriptions Implementation Steps: Create templates in AgenticFlow for each common scenario Set up decision logic based on task requirements Integrate with your platform accounts for automatic execution Build monitoring dashboard for workflow performance Expected ROI: 80% time reduction in workflow setup and 95% reduction in manual product uploads. This system will transform your disorganized bulk workflow into a streamlined, automated machine that handles hundreds of products with minimal manual intervention. The combination recommended above gives you the best balance of power, ease-of-use, and cost-effectiveness for your specific e-commerce automation needs. I have a lot of sass tools in my tech stack. Would it make sense to spend an hour and just create common integrations across all these, or is it better to use some type of an mcp? Where the mcp has my tech stack, and it's not a lot of individual ap. I calls across these automation tools would be the best way to make sure that when I have a project, I have less friction. What's the setup process that would be the most optimized right now? I know that there are some